184
00:16:46,160 --> 00:16:52,560
write the SQL for you now, but you still need to 
write SQL yourself. And every single time I wrote  

185
00:16:52,560 --> 00:16:57,920
a SQL query, I wanted to run the same subsequent 
analysis. I wanted great version control, I wanted  

186
00:16:57,920 --> 00:17:06,920
all the cool stuff that GitHub had for code but 
for writing data code. And so my friends and I  

187
00:17:06,920 --> 00:17:15,720
built a little Python tool which basically let you 
run our style queries. It lets you draw charts and  

188
00:17:15,720 --> 00:17:24,400
pivot tables quickly and sharing all this modern 
SaaS application stuff. But applied to SQL a few  

189
00:17:24,400 --> 00:17:30,920
years ago and we turned that into a company.
We got some progress, but then there was this  

190
00:17:30,920 --> 00:17:40,200
moment one day where we had maybe a couple 100 
customers and we had an error where we basically  

191
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:47,680
by accidentally shut down the service and it 
was bricked for 10 or 20 minutes. And at the  

192
00:17:47,680 --> 00:17:54,240
time we were hustling in our little dinky office 
to get the application back online. And we really  

193
00:17:54,840 --> 00:18:00,680
were proud of ourselves about how reasonably 
quickly we did and people went back to using  

194
00:18:00,680 --> 00:18:05,760
it. It wasn't a super long outage and we didn't 
lose any data. We were just high-fiving each  

195
00:18:05,760 --> 00:18:11,440
other. And we went about our day and about 
a year later I realized that that was a... 

196
00:18:11,440 --> 00:18:19,240
I missed a huge moment that I should have pounced 
on, which is that during those 20 minutes,  

197
00:18:19,240 --> 00:18:27,480
our customers weren't furious. They weren't 
emailing us like crazy, they weren't texting us,  

198
00:18:27,480 --> 00:18:31,880
they weren't trying to find us on Google 
Maps and knock on our door and say, "Hey,  

199
00:18:31,880 --> 00:18:37,000
I need this thing back online immediately." 
We heard a couple comments from them,  

200
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:42,520
it was little murmurs. And I didn't realize at 
the time that was the signal that we did not  

201
00:18:42,520 --> 00:18:48,960
have product market fit. And I ended up wasting 
many more years on that project. And wasting is  

202
00:18:48,960 --> 00:18:53,560
a big word. We built amazing software, people 
liked it, we were able to sell the company. 

203
00:18:53,560 --> 00:19:00,440
It helped many of us learn how to really build 
software. But I'm really trying to avoid that  

204
00:19:00,440 --> 00:19:10,280
situation again. And I think craft is a dessert 
that you get after the meal of does your thing  

205
00:19:10,280 --> 00:19:18,560
solve a real problem in the world and are people 
clamoring, needing it badly? And that's really my  

206
00:19:18,560 --> 00:19:26,880
obsession is in finding problems in which people 
will pause their entire day to solve. They will  

207
00:19:26,880 --> 00:19:32,600
leap through the computer to be like, "Oh my God, 
I have that problem. Do you have a solution?" 

208
00:19:32,600 --> 00:19:39,640
And if you focus on that style of product 
development and we can get into just how do you  

209
00:19:40,760 --> 00:19:47,080
listen for that and then turn that into product. 
Later, you might get the opportunity to really  

210
00:19:47,080 --> 00:19:53,680
provide craft and beauty and touches and moments 
and delight. But certainly there is no amount of  

211
00:19:53,680 --> 00:19:58,960
craft, there is no amount of beauty, there's no 
amount delight or touches you can add to a thing  

212
00:19:58,960 --> 00:20:06,080
that will solve the problem we had at our startup, 
which is that people didn't really need this. And  

213
00:20:06,080 --> 00:20:11,200
that's the biggest error is picking something in 
which people don't really need it. And then going  

214
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:16,160
through these practices of trying to make it great 
when maybe it shouldn't exist in the first place.

215
00:20:16,160 --> 00:20:19,880
I think a lot of people see all these 
tweets and messages about just obsessed  

216
00:20:19,880 --> 00:20:26,640
with the craft of what you're building and 
you can easily lose sight of... Nobody even  

217
00:20:26,640 --> 00:20:31,160
cares about what you're building. It could be 
the most incredible experience ever designed,  

218
00:20:31,160 --> 00:20:34,520
but if it's not something anyone 
ever wants, it doesn't really matter.

219
00:20:34,520 --> 00:20:38,880
People don't really get out of bed for their 
second problem. They get out of bed for their  

220
00:20:38,880 --> 00:20:46,520
first problem. And you have to carefully listen 
and not pitch your customer or your prospective  

221
00:20:46,520 --> 00:20:50,840
customer as you're trying to figure this out. 
And I think this advice, not even advice just  

222
00:20:50,840 --> 00:20:57,960
style applies to small companies, big companies, 
anyone which is people don't want to be pitched.  

223
00:20:58,720 --> 00:21:03,600
I'm sometimes on a UXR call with a very 
well-meaning person or a founder who has  

224
00:21:03,600 --> 00:21:12,680
a new product that they want advice on or they 
want to find customers. And the first thing that  

225
00:21:12,680 --> 00:21:19,000
they start talking about when we get on the call 
is, "Hi, I'm the CEO of X, Y, and Z company. We do  

226
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:28,520
one, two, and three. I want to show you a demo." 
It's like, "Hold up, I'm a customer. I have..."  

227
00:21:30,640 --> 00:21:37,080
What a wasted opportunity you've just done here.
I have so many problems, you're guessing ahead of  

228
00:21:37,080 --> 00:21:43,200
time, what is my top problem and now that 
you've anchored and limited to the pitch  

229
00:21:43,200 --> 00:21:49,120
you're going to miss, you very likely going to 
miss the burning problem that they have on the  

230
00:21:49,120 --> 00:21:54,760
top of their mind. And it's not the customer's 
job to interrupt you and say, "Hey, could you  

231
00:21:54,760 --> 00:22:00,040
stop your pitch? I want to tell you about my top 
problem." And you can see this down the stream,  

232
00:22:00,040 --> 00:22:07,920
which then companies who launch things, put craft, 
have a great launch, raise money are then later  

233
00:22:07,920 --> 00:22:14,600
gone. And it's because they built something that 
wasn't solving a burning need. And I think you  

234
00:22:14,600 --> 00:22:21,600
can stem it all the way back to they were just 
pitching rather than sitting in silence and just  

235
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:28,680
waiting for their customer to just open their 
heart out about what's the most burning thing. 

236
00:22:28,680 --> 00:22:34,120
And sometimes I'll prompt our customers, I'll 
say, "Hey, do you mind just opening up your email?  

237
00:22:34,120 --> 00:22:39,320
What's in there?" Or, "If you weren't talking to 
me right now, what would you be working on?" Or,  

238
00:22:39,320 --> 00:22:45,640
"Hey, last week, what grinds your gears? What 
are you not looking forward to?" Or magic wand,  

239
00:22:45,640 --> 00:22:49,880
"What do you wish you could just have off your 
plate immediately? Forget Stripe, forget about  

240
00:22:49,880 --> 00:22:57,680
thing, work on just in your whole life. What is it 
that you do not want to be doing?" Or, "A massive  

241
00:22:57,680 --> 00:23:04,680
opportunity you wish was just one door away?" And 
it's a little awkward because they don't know why  

242
00:23:04,680 --> 00:23:09,760
you're asking that kind of question, but then you 
just sit there in silence. And for the most part,  

243
00:23:09,760 --> 00:23:13,360
if you have amazing customers who are 
smart and ambitious and are trying to  

244
00:23:13,360 --> 00:23:17,640
build their own business, they're going to want 
to offload their hardest thing to somebody else. 

245
00:23:17,640 --> 00:23:21,880
If you've earned trust along the way, and 
certainly not pitching is a great way of earning  

246
00:23:21,880 --> 00:23:26,440
trust. You're just listening. We've learned a 
lot at Stripe from that. And that's where you  

247
00:23:26,440 --> 00:23:31,120
can start to find adjacencies, right? "Well, hey, 
I don't know if Stripe could really help me with  

248
00:23:31,120 --> 00:23:38,600
this, but wouldn't it be cool if we could identify 
if the person signing up on our site wasn't  

249
00:23:38,600 --> 00:23:44,150
fraudulent or is who they say they are or isn't 
a bot, or are they really a dog on the internet?"  

250
00:23:44,150 --> 00:23:49,080
And we're like, "We keep this as the major 
complaint from all of our customers, but we're  

251
00:23:49,080 --> 00:23:55,000
not an identity company." It's like, "Well, I 
guess now we are because all of our customers who  

252
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:02,360
are trying to build their business all have this 
problem." And so via silence, you can just create  

253
00:24:02,360 --> 00:24:15,080
your roadmap pretty quickly and drop a lot of the 
long UXR, long survey, long build cycle approach.

254
00:24:15,080 --> 00:24:18,040
So I love where we're going with this. This is 
where I was going to actually talk about next  

255
00:24:18,040 --> 00:24:23,800
is just your ability to talk to customers 
and user research. It feels very unique,  

256
00:24:23,800 --> 00:24:28,040
watching you operate on Twitter, you're 
just sharing your email constantly,  

257
00:24:28,040 --> 00:24:33,800
getting on calls with people constantly. There's 
this, you're breaking this wall between... That  

258
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:39,120
a lot of people imagine there is between the 
PM and the lead of a team and the customer.  

259
00:24:39,120 --> 00:24:43,160
You're not relying easy research. You're not 
waiting for someone else to do this work for  

260
00:24:43,160 --> 00:24:49,000
you. Talk about just why and how you do this. 
I think there's so much to learn from just how  

261
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:53,720
you operate in finding opportunities, picking 
problems to solve by talking to customers.

262
00:24:53,720 --> 00:25:03,200
It's where the business comes from is customers. 
It is not a long shot hypothesis about why to talk  

263
00:25:03,200 --> 00:25:08,920
to them. It's like if they love your stuff, they 
will tell their friends and pay fair prices for  

264
00:25:08,920 --> 00:25:20,360
the product. We're so fortunate through the 
internet that people announced themselves as  

265
00:25:20,360 --> 00:25:26,160
being interested in a topic. Sometimes they're 
interested in it by posting on Reddit a long  

266
00:25:26,160 --> 00:25:34,360
thread or a screenshot of a customer service 
interaction that bugged them or hopeful that  

267
00:25:34,360 --> 00:25:41,560
from their dorm room in country X, someone else 
in the world has solved the same problem. And  

268
00:25:41,560 --> 00:25:49,200
the internet has given us all this absolutely 
magical forum that you can just yell out the  

269
00:25:49,200 --> 00:25:55,600
window and then billions of people could actually 
listen to what you said out the window. Now,  

270
00:25:55,600 --> 00:26:03,080
that's not all the time true for all people 
in all situations, but dramatically more  

271
00:26:03,080 --> 00:26:07,680
true now than ever before in human history.
And so the fact that people wouldn't be listening  

272
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:16,440
to their customers and really jumping through the 
computer to talk to them surprises me. It's like I  

273
00:26:16,440 --> 00:26:22,200
always sometimes think, "Do they have some other 
strategy? Are they so confident in what they're  

274
00:26:22,200 --> 00:26:28,560
building that they don't need to hear directly 
from the people who will be using it?" And I think  

275
00:26:28,560 --> 00:26:34,120
some of it is my own fear that I'm going to 
make the same mistake I've made in the past,  

276
00:26:34,120 --> 00:26:41,400
which is build something that people like they're 
using but isn't solving a burning enough problem  

277
00:26:41,400 --> 00:26:45,320
such that they're going to stop their day, they're 
going to tell their friends, we're going to be  

278
00:26:45,320 --> 00:26:50,880
able to sustain the company economically over a 
long period of time. And that really just comes  

279
00:26:50,880 --> 00:26:57,520
from hearing people's most burning problems 
and then just jumping through the computer  

280
00:26:57,520 --> 00:27:05,840
and talking to them takes a little bit of nervous 
gumption, like walking up to a person at a bar or  

281
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:11,120
cocktail party and saying, "Hi, my name is Jeff."
It can be a little awkward, but then you get it.  

282
00:27:11,120 --> 00:27:18,560
It's a rush once it starts to work. And once 
you get the iterative loop that they're excited  

283
00:27:18,560 --> 00:27:26,080
to talk to you, they have problems, they see 
you as a trusted, not salesy, not pitching,  

284
00:27:26,080 --> 00:27:32,920
not narrow-minded to just my product and 
my position, but I'm here to hear about all  

285
00:27:32,920 --> 00:27:36,760
of your problems and see where we can help. 
Not promising we can help solve everything,  

286
00:27:36,760 --> 00:27:42,760
but let's listen. That is infectious, both between 
the customers and internally. And so I'm able to  

287
00:27:42,760 --> 00:27:49,760
bring more people into that practice. At Stripe, 
I'm able to quickly grab an engineer and hop on  

288
00:27:49,760 --> 00:27:58,280
a call. I can forward a message over to a Slack 
group. And they know that because the customer's  

289
00:27:58,280 --> 00:28:02,880
speaking directly, it somewhat trumps everything 
that's happening during the day. We could go to  

290
00:28:02,880 --> 00:28:08,120
our meeting where we're going to guess what the 
customer wants or we could talk to them directly. 

291
00:28:08,800 --> 00:28:16,960
And you have to use a little bit of art to decide 
which customers you want to listen the closest to.  

292
00:28:16,960 --> 00:28:22,720
But even at Stripe's scale, where we're dealing 
with many millions of businesses and many hundreds  

293
00:28:22,720 --> 00:28:29,240
of millions of consumers on the other end of 
those businesses, you can pattern match relatively  

294
00:28:29,240 --> 00:28:35,200
quickly. What are the styles of customers 
that represent where the world is going, the  

295
00:28:35,200 --> 00:28:41,440
most ambitious, the most technical, the fastest 
growing, the most detailed. And you don't need  

296
00:28:41,440 --> 00:28:48,920
10,000 of those people to talk to. If you're text 
message friendly with five or 10 of those, you are  

297
00:28:48,920 --> 00:28:57,680
going to have so much direct signal about where 
to go that you forget how you did it in the past.

298
00:28:57,680 --> 00:29:02,200
I love these. So I'd love to learn more about 
these tactics that you've found helpful.  

299
00:29:02,200 --> 00:29:06,720
So you've shared this idea of silence, 
talking to someone and just being silent,  

300
00:29:06,720 --> 00:29:10,800
and I forget the phrase you used, but just like 
ideas emerge, like your whole road map can emerge  

301
00:29:10,800 --> 00:29:13,720
from that silence. So let me share a few of 
the things you shared so far and I'm curious  

302
00:29:13,720 --> 00:29:18,000
what else. Two is tweeting just like, "Hey, 
I'm looking to improve Atlas right now. What  

303
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:22,720
bugs do you have? Here's my email address." 
You talked about text messaging, just like,  

304
00:29:22,720 --> 00:29:26,120
"Hey, can I get your number? And I'll just text 
you when I have questions." If there's anything  

305
00:29:26,120 --> 00:29:29,040
else to add to these, that'd be awesome. 
And then what else have you found? Just  

306
00:29:29,040 --> 00:29:34,640
ways to actually get to a customer and 
find opportunities that are important.

307
00:29:34,640 --> 00:29:43,760
Speed is an important one, which is just reducing 
the time between the moment the customer felt  

308
00:29:43,760 --> 00:29:51,480
compelled enough to go out of their way to talk 
about some problem. They're busy, there are snacks  

309
00:29:51,480 --> 00:29:58,040
to eat, they have families, they have other things 
to do. There's a lot going on in the world, a lot.  

310
00:29:59,280 --> 00:30:05,440
Your dumb product, it's amazing that they 
would spend any of their time discussing it  

311
00:30:05,440 --> 00:30:10,600
at all. I mean, most of the time if you don't 
like something, you just move along. You just  

312
00:30:10,600 --> 00:30:15,680
apathetically, silently move forward in 
the world. And so the fact that someone  

313
00:30:15,680 --> 00:30:23,800
took their finite time to succinctly with 
curiosity, communicate to the world or you  

314
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:33,880
about your product, that's a unbelievable gift.
That should be P-zero alert level intensity. And  

315
00:30:33,880 --> 00:30:43,160
so I will leave a meeting, I will change what 
I'm doing to just get one message back to them.  

316
00:30:43,160 --> 00:30:48,520
Even if it's, "Hey, I got this. I'm about to go to 
dinner. Can I hit you up tomorrow?" They're like,  

317
00:30:48,520 --> 00:30:52,400
"Oh yeah, thank you. Awesome. I can't even 
believe you responded." That puts us in the  

318
00:30:52,400 --> 00:30:58,000
camp of on the right trajectory where they're 
going to feel that they have a almost secret  

319
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:03,931
portal between this big brand of a company and 
another human who's just actually curious...

320
00:31:03,931 --> 00:31:04,720
... brand of a company and another human 
who's just actually curious what's going on,  

321
00:31:04,720 --> 00:31:11,360
that's night and day. And it's also, fun fact, 
tip, when people are really hot on an issue and  

322
00:31:11,360 --> 00:31:18,040
it could blow up on social or they're going to 
start becoming a detractor, we make mistakes,  

323
00:31:18,040 --> 00:31:25,280
we have SLA breaches, we have errors, you're 
going to want to get on that stuff fast. And in  

324
00:31:25,280 --> 00:31:33,240
those situations, my bar for how we will respond 
to those folks is not to just solve the problem,  

325
00:31:33,240 --> 00:31:37,360
but it is to turn them into a promoter, 
and most of the time we're able to,  

326
00:31:37,360 --> 00:31:44,080
even if there was a pretty relevant issue.
I remember one time at Atlas, we had this  

327
00:31:44,080 --> 00:31:51,000
bug in which for a handful of our legal 
docs, they were handing out let's say,  

328
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:58,040
25 shares rather than 25% of the shares. We 
dropped the percentage sign, and thankfully  

329
00:31:58,040 --> 00:32:05,720
a founder noticed this in the docs and tweeted 
about it. My heart paused and I was like, "Oh no,  

330
00:32:05,720 --> 00:32:09,920
this could be a really serious issue." And we 
were able to fix it and regenerate the documents  

331
00:32:09,920 --> 00:32:15,640
relatively quickly for everyone that was impacted. 
And I was thinking to myself, "Wow, we really let  

332
00:32:15,640 --> 00:32:20,800
this person down. We have one job to do, which 
is to get their company right and we didn't." 

333
00:32:20,800 --> 00:32:28,520
And that person was incredibly gracious about 
the situation and said, "Anytime you want me  

334
00:32:28,520 --> 00:32:33,840
to just read your docs, I'd be happy to. I have 
a law degree. I care about this topic. I want  

335
00:32:33,840 --> 00:32:38,240
to brainstorm with you about ways that Atlas 
could do more document creations." I was like,  

336
00:32:38,240 --> 00:32:43,640
"Wow, I can't believe I was in this sort 
of defense position, and now we've gained  

337
00:32:43,640 --> 00:32:49,240
a friend in the world who can be eyes and ears 
and brainstorm with us." And the team maintains  

338
00:32:49,240 --> 00:32:53,120
a really close relationship with that person as 
they do with many, many founders who use Atlas. 

339
00:32:53,120 --> 00:32:59,920
And so, just again, we're so quick to put 
the outside world in this other camp where  

340
00:32:59,920 --> 00:33:08,000
we need to touch it with kid gloves and treat 
it as a big blob and a cohort and a statistic,  

341
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:14,120
when it is a human with a problem who likes 
snacks, who is busy, and it's fun to do and  

342
00:33:14,120 --> 00:33:19,800
it turns out to be an incredibly easy, 
fast way to figure out what to build.

343
00:33:19,800 --> 00:33:23,640
There's a bunch of stuff I want to follow up 
here. One is, people may be hearing this and like,  

344
00:33:23,640 --> 00:33:29,240
"Oh my God, I'd be overwhelmed with feedback 
and people to fix problems for and bugs and  

345
00:33:29,240 --> 00:33:34,880
texting of people." They're just like, 
"There's so many people that potentially  

346
00:33:34,880 --> 00:33:39,240
I'd have to be interacting with." How do 
you try to narrow that down? I know Atlas  

347
00:33:39,240 --> 00:33:43,520
is a very highly adopted product. There's 
a ton of people, there's probably bugs,  

348
00:33:43,520 --> 00:33:47,000
often people sending you feedback. How 
do you pick the people to zero in on?

349
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:52,320
I think there are two parts to this. One, what a 
problem to have. Of all the problems in the world,  

350
00:33:52,320 --> 00:34:00,560
"I'm overwhelmed by customer interest," is 
on the top list of problems I want to have.  

351
00:34:00,560 --> 00:34:08,600
I think most entrepreneurs would purchase that 
problem as a state. And so, if you're in it,  

352
00:34:08,600 --> 00:34:13,760
I think, take a deep breath and look at the 
sunrise or sunset and just enjoy the fact that  

353
00:34:13,760 --> 00:34:19,720
you've built something that is meaningful enough 
that people would spend their time. Again, there  

354
00:34:19,720 --> 00:34:27,720
are amazing snacks that they could be spending 
the time on otherwise, so that's a huge deal.  

355
00:34:28,880 --> 00:34:33,880
And then two, you need the art. There's 
an art and science to picking where to  

356
00:34:33,880 --> 00:34:38,840
go deep. I will happily respond to folks 
with, "I really appreciate that. Do you  

357
00:34:38,840 --> 00:34:45,520
mind sending me a screenshot or a video?" 
And some of them don't. Okay, that's fine. 

358
00:34:45,520 --> 00:34:52,600
You kind of get a sense of quickly looking at how 
they wrote about it or just pattern matching how  

359
00:34:52,600 --> 00:35:01,200
detailed they were, or how much they seem that 
they want to engage and kind of balance it that  

360
00:35:01,200 --> 00:35:09,760
way. Otherwise, you can tell folks, "This 
is really awesome. Do you mind sending me  

361
00:35:09,760 --> 00:35:17,920
an email with three to five bullet points about 
the details of how you got to this issue?" And  

362
00:35:17,920 --> 00:35:22,880
that's not a 30-minute meeting. You don't need 
to blow up your whole life to get on the phone  

363
00:35:22,880 --> 00:35:30,160
with them. It's not a huge homework assignment 
to them, but it's enough structure that it will  

364
00:35:30,160 --> 00:35:35,920
self-select those who want to go deep, and then 
from there, you really do owe it to them to follow  

365
00:35:35,920 --> 00:35:40,840
up if they're going to be that detailed. And 
at that point, you really have made a product  

366
00:35:40,840 --> 00:35:48,440
friend for life and you'll kind of continuously 
go back to them. So you have to kind of tune it. 

367
00:35:48,440 --> 00:35:56,760
I also will bound some of these efforts, so I'll 
just completely make up one day a program. So,  

368
00:35:56,760 --> 00:36:04,000
"Hi, Stripe's doing a bug-finder program." I made 
that up as I was driving to work one morning,  

369
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:09,320
tweeted it, was curious if anyone would send 
anything. "We'll be taking videos for the next  

370
00:36:09,320 --> 00:36:13,960
three days to go super deep." And people are 
like, "Oh my goodness, I would love to be part  

371
00:36:13,960 --> 00:36:21,280
of the Stripe bug-finder program. May I apply?" 
I'm like, "Oh, it's very selective. But yes,  

372
00:36:21,280 --> 00:36:27,560
of course for you." It's just giving people 
permission through a program, even if it is  

373
00:36:28,080 --> 00:36:33,800
deeply arbitrary, I find helps with bounding it, 
and then later I can follow up with the world,  

374
00:36:33,800 --> 00:36:41,720
"Hey, we ran our first program, we got 65 videos," 
which we did. "We found dozens of issues," which  

375
00:36:41,720 --> 00:36:53,400
we did. It was an incredibly valuable use of our 
time and it really came from just a single tweet.

376
00:36:53,400 --> 00:36:57,000
Something I saw you mention somewhere is 
that you only pay attention to feedback from  

377
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:00,680
people that are paying customers and ignore 
everything else. Can you talk about that?

378
00:37:00,680 --> 00:37:08,000
People who build things for people tend to be 
empathetic and interested and curious folks who  

379
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:15,160
have friends, and then those friends want to use 
your stuff because they know you and they like  

380
00:37:15,160 --> 00:37:23,840
you and they'll have good feedback. But you need 
to figure out, is that actually your customer,  

381
00:37:23,840 --> 00:37:31,560
or is that your friend trying it? Who is actually 
your target customer exactly? Not a company or a  

382
00:37:31,560 --> 00:37:39,360
segment, not digital natives that are X big. 
I'm talking about Sarah in this department,  

383
00:37:39,360 --> 00:37:46,640
who has these tabs open and just faced this 
problem and needs to solve it by 4:00 PM.  

384
00:37:46,640 --> 00:37:53,480
That level of specificity. If that's your 
customer, and I'm talking mostly about B2B,  

385
00:37:53,480 --> 00:37:58,640
which is where I spend a lot of my time as the 
social network, B2C stuff I have less intuition  

386
00:37:58,640 --> 00:38:09,360
on, they're very willing to exchange money for 
solving their problems, incredibly so. Oftentimes,  

387
00:38:10,240 --> 00:38:13,960
if you listen with enough silence, they 
might even say, "I'll pay you money to solve,  

388
00:38:13,960 --> 00:38:20,800
blah." If you sit there long enough in silence.
And so, you could listen to your friendly friend  

389
00:38:20,800 --> 00:38:25,080
who you got to play with your beta version 
and they'll say they liked it and they will  

390
00:38:25,080 --> 00:38:30,200
click around. But that is extremely different from 
Sarah, who has the actual problem and is willing  

391
00:38:30,200 --> 00:38:39,520
to pay. And it is so tempting to go down the first 
path with the friend group that I sort of needed a  

392
00:38:39,520 --> 00:38:43,840
rule, which was like, "Okay, rather than..." I was 
like, "Well, don't pay attention to that quite as  

393
00:38:43,840 --> 00:38:48,920
much. Really pay attention to, who is your target 
customer and are you in a fast iteration cycle  

394
00:38:48,920 --> 00:38:53,080
for them and are they telling their friends?"
But that wasn't enough, because people are so  

395
00:38:53,080 --> 00:38:59,040
drawn, myself included, drawn to the friendliness 
that I just set a rule, which is, "We discount all  

396
00:38:59,040 --> 00:39:06,040
of that feedback from our friends to zero." That 
is not of interest to us. We don't even write it  

397
00:39:06,040 --> 00:39:13,160
down. It's just not part of what we're talking 
about at all. We are only interested in Sarah,  

398
00:39:13,160 --> 00:39:20,840
our target customer, and can we get her to solve 
whatever the problem is as quickly as possible,  

399
00:39:20,840 --> 00:39:30,240
as jangly as possible and go from there?
And then the paying part is a forcing  

400
00:39:30,240 --> 00:39:35,600
function because again, even with Sarah, because 
you're paying attention to her and solving her  

401
00:39:35,600 --> 00:39:42,280
problem a bit, she'll say, "Of course, oh, this is 
great. I want feature X, Y and Z. Can it do one,  

402
00:39:42,280 --> 00:39:47,880
two, and three?" Naturally, she would say that. 
But if you said, "And by the way, this thing is  

403
00:39:47,880 --> 00:39:54,840
$10,000. We'll happily refund your money 100% the 
second you don't like it," she might say, "Whoa,  

404
00:39:54,840 --> 00:40:04,320
whoa, wait a second. Yeah, I like this thing, but 
not $10, 000. For $10,000, it would need to solve  

405
00:40:04,320 --> 00:40:10,920
X." And you're like, "Oh, there it is." That 
was actually what the thing that was of value,  

406
00:40:10,920 --> 00:40:17,960
and we were all kind of dancing around 
this. It's useful, we're on the right track,  

407
00:40:17,960 --> 00:40:24,840
and because I've fallen down that path 
myself so many times, I just set a rule.

408
00:40:24,840 --> 00:40:29,920
This is great. I was actually going to ask. 
This technique of using silence, to help  

409
00:40:29,920 --> 00:40:35,480
people actually practice it, you just shared this 
quote of, "For you to pay $10,000 it would've to  

410
00:40:35,480 --> 00:40:38,720
do X." That's a really cool line to use. Is 
there any other advice there of just how to  

411
00:40:38,720 --> 00:40:45,200
practice this idea of creating silence to help a 
potential customer share what they actually need?

412
00:40:45,200 --> 00:40:52,360
I encourage people to take an improv training 
class or two, just to get people out of their  

413
00:40:52,360 --> 00:40:57,520
skin a bit. By the way, this advice applies 
to big companies also, not just small ones.  

414
00:40:57,520 --> 00:41:03,960
And we have issues, and I hear other larger 
companies have issues where a big company will  

415
00:41:03,960 --> 00:41:11,280
say, "Hey, we're an enterprise and we're going to 
pay you this big contract. All you need to do is  

416
00:41:11,280 --> 00:41:14,720
build features one, two, three, four, five, six, 
seven, eight, nine, and go through security steps,  

417
00:41:14,720 --> 00:41:20,720
A, B, C, D, E, F, G." And this siren song of the 
big three-year contract of your first enterprise  

418
00:41:20,720 --> 00:41:27,280
buyer, even when you're already big, you 
can go from Fortune 1000 to Fortune 500 to  

419
00:41:27,280 --> 00:41:32,680
Fortune 10 to Fortune 1. There's always 
more. There are so many stories of the  

420
00:41:32,680 --> 00:41:38,240
rug being pulled in the middle and they never 
actually use it and the contract never lands. 

421
00:41:38,240 --> 00:41:44,080
Same in partnerships. And so, I would say the same 
thing, which is, "If we're super serious about  

422
00:41:44,080 --> 00:41:51,840
this, send us $1 million. Wire us $1 million. 
We'll happily wire it back anytime you need it,  

423
00:41:51,840 --> 00:41:59,760
but let's actually put some stake in the ground 
about the value." And I find that in the cases in  

424
00:41:59,760 --> 00:42:05,200
which they're like, "Whoa, wait a second, no, 
absolutely not. We can't commit here." That's  

425
00:42:05,200 --> 00:42:10,200
really a good signal because you're about to spend 
a huge amount of time building something that  

426
00:42:10,200 --> 00:42:15,840
might not ever be used, and that's the majority 
case I hear. Or you might get the opposite, which  

427
00:42:15,840 --> 00:42:24,520
is, "Sounds great. Let's make sure our teams are 
trained on it faster. How can we get you to our  

428
00:42:24,520 --> 00:42:29,680
office to explain it? We need it to really work 
with this system we haven't talked about yet. And  

429
00:42:29,680 --> 00:42:35,840
now that we're paying, we want it even faster."
And so, I find that it puts a fork in the road  

430
00:42:35,840 --> 00:42:44,880
towards faster success or avoiding the non-success 
case. And even at Stripe scale, I've heard our  

431
00:42:44,880 --> 00:42:50,920
founders somewhat push this methodology on 
us, where one from the outside might think,  

432
00:42:50,920 --> 00:42:57,320
"Well, it's a 8,000 person company. Surely they 
have just regular ways of building things for  

433
00:42:57,320 --> 00:43:04,320
larger customers, and we too need these style of 
commitments if we're going to go off roadmap."

434
00:43:04,320 --> 00:43:08,520
So a big lesson you're sharing here is 
essentially, make sure people are ready  

435
00:43:08,520 --> 00:43:13,424
to pay for something that they're asking 
for. That is the ultimate sign that they-

436
00:43:13,424 --> 00:43:18,280
And by the way, ready to pay is different 
than paying. Significantly different,  

437
00:43:18,280 --> 00:43:23,240
significantly different. I've also thought 
of, "Well, as long as they're ready to pay  

438
00:43:23,240 --> 00:43:28,200
and they said they would pay and they look at the 
contract, we should feel good." That is not the  

439
00:43:28,200 --> 00:43:35,320
same as paying. Paying is an independent group 
of people saying, "My problem is burning enough  

440
00:43:35,320 --> 00:43:41,040
that I'm willing to exchange something I have 
that has value for the promise of what you're  

441
00:43:41,040 --> 00:43:47,360
going to do." And now it's a real commitment. 
That is extremely different than ready to. So  

442
00:43:47,360 --> 00:43:57,040
I will often be on the phone or video, whatever 
with a founder and I will have them practice  

443
00:43:59,280 --> 00:44:05,520
charging me. I'll just say, "Hey, I'm just 
a friend. I'm trying to help you out. It's a  

444
00:44:06,040 --> 00:44:08,840
little bit self-serving because I work at Stripe 
and I want to get feedback on our products." 

445
00:44:08,840 --> 00:44:15,720
I'll say, "Feel free to sign up for any invoicing 
or payment service. I don't really care which  

446
00:44:15,720 --> 00:44:19,680
one. You're welcome to choose Stripe if it's easy 
enough for you, I'd love to hear your two cents,  

447
00:44:19,680 --> 00:44:26,400
and send me an invoice or a payment link 
for $1 right now, right now. That way,  

448
00:44:27,640 --> 00:44:32,440
when it comes time to actually charge your first 
customer, it won't be your first time. It won't  

449
00:44:32,440 --> 00:44:36,800
feel weird. You'll have already done this, you 
already have a dollar in your account, you already  

450
00:44:36,800 --> 00:44:41,680
have your logo on the top right of the invoice. 
It'll feel great." And I probably could go through  

451
00:44:41,680 --> 00:44:48,800
my email inbox and just see $1 receipts to random 
people because I'm just so convinced that the  

452
00:44:48,800 --> 00:44:57,040
difference between paying and willing, ready, I 
thought they would pay is night and day different.

453
00:44:57,840 --> 00:45:02,640
Yeah, there's this term, willingness to 
pay that I feel like it should change,  

454
00:45:02,640 --> 00:45:05,320
as you're saying, to just cross 
that willingness to even just-

455
00:45:05,320 --> 00:45:05,920
Paying.

456
00:45:05,920 --> 00:45:07,000
Paying, exactly.

457
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:12,600
Yeah. And we can refund the money. There's 
no issue at all. Just other tricks on how to  

458
00:45:12,600 --> 00:45:22,200
get people going is, ask them about their regular 
life as a human, "What did you do yesterday?" And  

459
00:45:22,200 --> 00:45:28,920
they'll be like, "Oh, at work?" I'm like, "Or not. 
Whatever." And people, they'll start to spill,  

460
00:45:28,920 --> 00:45:33,400
they'll just start to spill and eventually they'll 
get to their biggest problem pretty quickly.

461
00:45:33,400 --> 00:45:37,320
Let's talk about metrics, going in a 
different direction. Many people told me  

462
00:45:37,320 --> 00:45:41,280
I need to ask you about picking metrics and 
the importance of metrics and how you think  

463
00:45:41,280 --> 00:45:46,640
about metrics. So let me just maybe start 
with a question of, just why do you think  

464
00:45:46,640 --> 00:45:52,640
picking the right metric and why are metrics 
so important in building successful products?

465
00:45:52,640 --> 00:45:56,920
I somewhat walk around with the belief that  

466
00:45:58,400 --> 00:46:06,680
the product manager's responsibility is to produce 
product market fit. And okay, how do you know you  

467
00:46:06,680 --> 00:46:15,960
have product market fit? Charts that showcase 
things are going up into the right on one hand,  

468
00:46:15,960 --> 00:46:23,960
and then tweets on the other. So metrics like 
quantitative and qualitative, and I really see  

469
00:46:23,960 --> 00:46:33,760
them as deep siblings and equals, you really need 
both. It's not oh, OKRs versus something. There  

470
00:46:33,760 --> 00:46:41,400
are some things you want the texture of the person 
on video showing how complicated a thing was. And  

471
00:46:41,400 --> 00:46:46,920
then also, we're trying to make an economically 
viable system that we can run at large scale and  

472
00:46:46,920 --> 00:46:51,200
you can't keep all that stuff in your head and 
need to measure it. And so, I think metrics at  

473
00:46:51,200 --> 00:46:59,600
their best are a numerical representation of 
the value we're providing for the customer. 

474
00:46:59,600 --> 00:47:03,360
One could measure anything. You can just start 
counting events and log lines. We've made it  

475
00:47:03,360 --> 00:47:08,320
incredibly cheap to count stuff. And so, now 
we have this big privilege of choosing what  

476
00:47:08,320 --> 00:47:13,760
to measure. And I really just try to map it all 
the way back to, "Well, what was actually the  

477
00:47:13,760 --> 00:47:17,280
value that we're trying to produce for the 
customer and can we measure it from their  

478
00:47:17,280 --> 00:47:23,880
perspective?" Whereas I think it's natural, 
both because when you work inside of a company,  

479
00:47:23,880 --> 00:47:28,200
you're just thinking internally, but also the 
way that the metrics are collected inside your  

480
00:47:28,200 --> 00:47:36,880
application to be more internal-oriented. How many 
people logged in? Okay, that's a fine measure,  

481
00:47:36,880 --> 00:47:41,600
but how many people accomplished what they 
were trying to do after they logged in,  

482
00:47:41,600 --> 00:47:46,200
is not just necessarily sitting there as a 
single event in your database. You have to  

483
00:47:46,200 --> 00:47:53,720
think about it a bit. Another reason why I spend 
a lot of time crafting a small number of these  

484
00:47:53,720 --> 00:48:00,760
metrics is, they force trade-offs and decisions.
So we could all sit around all day and say, "Hey,  

485
00:48:00,760 --> 00:48:04,400
I heard all these customer problems, we should 
build X, Y, and Z." And another person could  

486
00:48:04,400 --> 00:48:07,880
absolutely reasonably say, "Well, I heard from 
these customers, we should build one, two and  

487
00:48:07,880 --> 00:48:13,280
three." And they're all true. We could have a lot 
of success in both, but the majority case is that  

488
00:48:13,280 --> 00:48:19,320
we don't build either and we sit around and 
argue and bicker and we go slowly. "What are  

489
00:48:19,320 --> 00:48:27,240
we going to do to naturally, organically every 
day, orient a larger group of people in the right  

490
00:48:27,240 --> 00:48:33,080
direction and see if our tactics are generating 
progress over time for a customer from their  

491
00:48:33,080 --> 00:48:41,320
perspective?" And metrics on the left and a series 
of tweets on the right is a pretty great combo. 

492
00:48:42,280 --> 00:48:49,520
Here's an example. A couple years ago I had been 
working in our payments group at Stripe for a bit,  

493
00:48:49,520 --> 00:48:56,040
and then I started working on some of our 
banking and incorporation services. In Atlas,  

494
00:48:56,040 --> 00:49:02,440
when I started working on it, it had had some 
success. It had already existed for four or  

495
00:49:02,440 --> 00:49:09,520
five years prior to me spending time on it. But 
when I started to look at the support tickets,  

496
00:49:09,520 --> 00:49:18,080
people were pretty unhappy frequently. They had 
a DocuSign stuck in their email box. They needed  

497
00:49:18,080 --> 00:49:23,400
a co-founder's address, but they didn't know 
their co-founder's address. They couldn't log  

498
00:49:23,400 --> 00:49:31,040
into the dashboard to figure out their 83(b) 
manual filing instructions. And we saw this  

499
00:49:31,040 --> 00:49:33,640
basically in the first week of spending time 
on Atlas. I was just like, "Just show me all  

500
00:49:33,640 --> 00:49:37,640
the support tickets. Are they happy support 
tickets? People writing in being like, 'Oh,  

501
00:49:37,640 --> 00:49:41,440
I love this service, it's absolutely fantastic. 
Can you just do A, B, C more for me?' Or are they  

502
00:49:41,440 --> 00:49:44,800
sad support tickets?" And they're like, "Oh 
my God, they're all sad support tickets." 

503
00:49:44,800 --> 00:49:52,160
And so, we're just asking ourselves, "Well, why 
would someone recommend Atlas to a friend?" I was  

504
00:49:52,160 --> 00:49:56,920
like, "Well, it would have to accomplish A, 
B and C activities for them. It would have to  

505
00:49:56,920 --> 00:50:02,160
get their company, it would have to handle getting 
their tax ID from the IRS. It'd have to handle all  

506
00:50:02,160 --> 00:50:06,560
the downstream administrivia." But surely, if 
they had a bunch of support tickets at the end,  

507
00:50:06,560 --> 00:50:12,760
they're not going to go tell their friends to 
use this thing. We could measure all of the  

508
00:50:12,760 --> 00:50:18,640
intermediate parts, we could measure the success 
rate and the frequency of incorporation services  

509
00:50:18,640 --> 00:50:23,440
and we do all those things, but if you looked 
at the support tickets, there's just no way if  

510
00:50:23,440 --> 00:50:27,280
you had a support ticket, you would recommend it 
to a friend. And so, we suggested this metric to  

511
00:50:27,280 --> 00:50:36,520
ourselves, companies that have no support 
tickets through the incorporation service. 

512
00:50:36,520 --> 00:50:43,440
The whole process, from the moment you start the 
application open, actually the first page load  

513
00:50:43,440 --> 00:50:48,280
at the very beginning, all the way through the 
process waiting for the government, waiting for  

514
00:50:48,280 --> 00:50:54,520
the IRS, and we give you two more weeks to write 
into support. We give an extra buffer two weeks.  

515
00:50:54,520 --> 00:51:00,800
And if you get through that whole thing with no 
support tickets, that's a yes. If you have any  

516
00:51:00,800 --> 00:51:06,520
number of support tickets, that's a no. And we 
just looked at the percentage of founders that  

517
00:51:06,520 --> 00:51:11,120
were going through the service with zero support 
tickets, which is very different than looking at  

518
00:51:11,120 --> 00:51:17,320
an average, right? You could have the average 
as 0.3, but that doesn't necessarily mean that  

519
00:51:17,320 --> 00:51:23,240
they're getting to 0.2 is going to cause them 
to tell their friends more. And we looked, and  

520
00:51:23,240 --> 00:51:31,320
only 15% of founders were getting through Atlas 
with zero support tickets through that metric. 

521
00:51:31,320 --> 00:51:37,800
And I just thought, "Okay, well let's just drive 
that number way up, and let's look at the support  

522
00:51:37,800 --> 00:51:43,400
tickets aside what people are needing and we'll 
bake it into the product, and presumably it'll  

523
00:51:43,400 --> 00:51:49,320
fix it. People will like that more and then tell 
their friends." And over about 18 months, we took  

524
00:51:49,320 --> 00:51:56,520
that number from 15% to 85. We basically just 
flipped it. And you can look at the market share  

525
00:51:57,960 --> 00:52:07,280
plotted on the same timeframe and it's the same 
shape. And I think you have to find a measure  

526
00:52:07,280 --> 00:52:15,560
by which it speaks directly to what the customer 
wanted, and that if you accidentally leaked your  

527
00:52:15,560 --> 00:52:20,360
dashboard to them, your customer would be ecstatic 
to learn that that's what you were measuring the  

528
00:52:20,360 --> 00:52:25,480
whole time. If we were to showcase the internal 
Atlas metrics, which we often just screenshot  

529
00:52:25,480 --> 00:52:30,280
and publish, I think they'd be pretty happy 
to hear that we were spending all of our time  

530
00:52:30,280 --> 00:52:37,200
making sure that none of them had support tickets.
And it was incredibly encouraging and motivating  

531
00:52:37,200 --> 00:52:44,480
to the engineers on the team because we could 
just assign them a topic. "Hey, look at all  

532
00:52:44,480 --> 00:52:51,760
these support tickets. Why don't you come up with 
the product spec, the scope, the solution? Oh,  

533
00:52:51,760 --> 00:52:57,480
want to learn more? Just reply to the support 
ticket email, figure out what they need." And so,  

534
00:52:57,480 --> 00:53:07,560
we kind of turned all of the engineers on the team 
into PMs to go and one issue at a time, figure  

535
00:53:07,560 --> 00:53:12,280
out what needed to change and build products for 
it. And that's where we pushed forward on 83(b)  

536
00:53:12,280 --> 00:53:17,080
elections, automating it, sending in the mail 
for folks. We built our own signing service. 

537
00:53:17,080 --> 00:53:22,280
We turned everything into a click. We did just did 
sort of the obvious things we saw in the tickets,  

538
00:53:22,280 --> 00:53:31,680
but as the PM, I was able to just sort of, 
not on autopilot, but really sit back and have  

539
00:53:31,680 --> 00:53:36,840
content full conversations with engineers who 
were bringing solutions and ideas for product,  

540
00:53:36,840 --> 00:53:43,480
rather than one person going through all of the 
potential ideas, scoping them and assigning them.  

541
00:53:43,480 --> 00:53:48,280
And because it was based in what people were 
saying and wanted, it was very motivating for  

542
00:53:48,280 --> 00:53:56,120
everyone on the team. So somewhat long answer, 
but figuring out something in which every day  

543
00:53:56,120 --> 00:54:02,720
we can wake up and look at the same metric 
and with some confidence know what to do,  

544
00:54:02,720 --> 00:54:08,440
is so much better than, "Let's figure out what 
to do each month, and starting from scratch."

545
00:54:08,440 --> 00:54:13,280
I think this is amazing and important advice, 
just the power of a single metric that everyone  

546
00:54:13,280 --> 00:54:17,800
on the team can understand, rally around and use 
to prioritize the work they're doing. I've seen  

547
00:54:17,800 --> 00:54:23,760
exactly the same sort of impact. Funny enough, 
Airbnb, one of the teams actually had a metric  

548
00:54:23,760 --> 00:54:29,360
sort of like this, basically reducing the people 
