551
00:54:37,560 --> 00:54:41,600
let's encourage them to figure it out themselves." 
Is there anything you've learned about to try  

552
00:54:41,600 --> 00:54:47,240
to avoid these kind of second order effects 
that are of perverse incentives of a metric?

553
00:54:47,240 --> 00:54:53,520
We look at multiple metrics, but we will optimize 
around one and you have to use your own judgment  

554
00:54:53,520 --> 00:55:03,640
to look at some of these countermeasures and pick 
them. We would also, that would sort of be our  

555
00:55:03,640 --> 00:55:11,560
overarching metric for a year, but then we would 
pick specific tactical metrics about how we would  

556
00:55:11,560 --> 00:55:20,520
accomplish it. So just an example that both is how 
we solved a problem, but also it's just a style of  

557
00:55:20,520 --> 00:55:29,280
metric that was useful to us. Of course, some of 
these support tickets included things like, "I'm  

558
00:55:29,280 --> 00:55:34,880
waiting to hear back from Atlas about, if they're 
going to approve my application because Stripe is  

559
00:55:34,880 --> 00:55:42,600
required for very good reasons to evaluate certain 
