560
00:55:42,600 --> 00:55:51,120
worldwide products." So there is some, should be 
incredibly quick, but there is a bit of a review  

561
00:55:51,120 --> 00:55:56,440
process, and of course if you were not hearing 
back from us, you would be upset because you're  

562
00:55:56,440 --> 00:55:59,400
trying to make your company immediately, "This 
is ridiculous. Let's get back to us quickly." 

563
00:55:59,400 --> 00:56:04,680
And so, we knew that one of the reasons that 
people were writing to support was like, "Hey,  

564
00:56:04,680 --> 00:56:11,640
what's up with my review? What's going on?" And 
we knew that our tactic was just to drive up how  

565
00:56:11,640 --> 00:56:17,320
quickly we got to a final decision on folks and 
to reduce the number of overturned rejections,  

566
00:56:17,320 --> 00:56:22,040
where someone writes back in saying, "Hi, come 
on, I'm totally just making something reasonable.  

567
00:56:22,040 --> 00:56:28,520
What's up? Why did you reject me?" And so, we 
would pick these overarching single metric,  

568
00:56:28,520 --> 00:56:33,840
which was the companies with zero support tickets, 
but then we would have a specific KR that was  

569
00:56:33,840 --> 00:56:40,800
owned by an engineer, which is the tactic that 
we're going to do. And so, we would not allow  

570
00:56:40,800 --> 00:56:47,280
ourselves the perverse tactics to sort of just 
casually exist. We would choose which tactics  

571
00:56:47,280 --> 00:56:52,160
we're going to do and then set a metric for it.
And the other reason I love this metric is,  

572
00:56:52,720 --> 00:56:59,480
it's a cohort metric by which you're trying 
to drive something up into the left. Sometimes  

573
00:56:59,480 --> 00:57:04,120
people will get excited about a chart that goes 
up into the right, it's kind of a meme, "Oh,  

574
00:57:04,120 --> 00:57:09,520
that's going up to the right." I'm really excited 
about charts that go up into the left. So you have  

575
00:57:09,520 --> 00:57:17,160
to figure out some optimization that you're trying 
to maximize. And so, in this particular case of  

576
00:57:17,160 --> 00:57:22,880
this risk review, we would look at, "Hey, for 
the cohort of customers that started last month,  

577
00:57:22,880 --> 00:57:31,160
how quickly did we get them to their final risk 
review by number of days since they submitted?"  

578
00:57:31,160 --> 00:57:37,600
And so, you want a chart that looks a lot 
like, "Here we go, right up to the top."  

579
00:57:37,600 --> 00:57:43,880
Because you want 100% of your customers to get 
their final decision as quickly as possible. 

580
00:57:43,880 --> 00:57:48,240
Wouldn't you know it, when we looked at 
the chart, it was doing this. And so,  

581
00:57:48,240 --> 00:57:52,520
each month we would just make it a little better, 
a little better, a little up and to the left,  

582
00:57:52,520 --> 00:57:58,040
up and to the left, up and to the left. And now 
basically 100-ish percent of people get their risk  

583
00:57:58,040 --> 00:58:06,080
review within an hour, from a long tail taking a 
long time. And so, we would constrain the tactic  

584
00:58:06,080 --> 00:58:10,680
through a metric and then watch it through an 
optimization function. And then when we got to  

585
00:58:10,680 --> 00:58:14,200
a point where we were happy with the target, we 
could put down the tactic. That's another really  

586
00:58:14,200 --> 00:58:18,920
useful thing about metrics, you can decide when 
to stop a tactic because you get to some level of  

587
00:58:18,920 --> 00:58:23,280
success that you're comfortable with and you 
can always choose to pick it back up later.

588
00:58:23,280 --> 00:58:26,840
So there's some really cool lessons here of 
just how to pick a good metric. Just to kind  

589
00:58:26,840 --> 00:58:32,320
of maybe summarize what I'm hearing is, you 
kind of worked backwards from essentially NPS,  

590
00:58:32,320 --> 00:58:37,040
like, "Why aren't people recommending 
Atlas?" You found, "Okay, well people  

591
00:58:37,040 --> 00:58:40,200
that are complaining and having issues 
with support and running into problems,  

592
00:58:40,200 --> 00:58:42,880
most likely are going to be detractors, 
not going to want to recommend Atlas,  

593
00:58:42,880 --> 00:58:48,840
so let's have those really ambitious goals. 
Eventually nobody has a support ticket/let's  

594
00:58:48,840 --> 00:58:53,560
just track how many people have zero issues." And 
then you identify, "Okay, what's driving a lot  

595
00:58:53,560 --> 00:58:57,960
of these support tickets? It looks like this risk 
timeline till they get to this certain milestone,  

596
00:58:57,960 --> 00:59:02,360
let's make that our goal for the next quarter 
or whatever, and let's focus there and then  

597
00:59:02,360 --> 00:59:07,960
make an impact." And then I imagine move on to 
other levers within this bucket of zero context.

598
00:59:07,960 --> 00:59:16,680
You have to pick the right metric for your 
audience in... I wouldn't wouldn't fully export  

599
00:59:16,680 --> 00:59:24,640
that metric to everyone. That was not a terrible 
one to export, but in the founders choosing where  

600
00:59:24,640 --> 00:59:31,400
to get started mindset, again, this isn't just 
